<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<section xml:id="monomial_orders_and_division" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Monomial Orders and Division</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      These are some examples of various monomial orderings with Sage, and an implementation of the division algorithm for multivariate polynomial rings (p. 65 of the text).
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="monomial_orders">
    <title>Monomial Orders</title>
    <p>
      The point of monomial orders is to export computations from univariate polynomial rings to analogous computations for multivariate polynomial rings.
      In SageMath, monomial orders are called <url href="https://doc.sagemath.org/html/en/reference/polynomial_rings/sage/rings/polynomial/term_order.html">term orders</url>, and several are implemented in the main libraries.
      For our purposes, we will primarily be concerned with SageMath's <c>lex</c>, <c>deglex</c> (graded lex), and <c>degrevlex</c> (graded reverse lex order).
    </p>
    <remark>
      <p>
	The default monomoial order in SageMath is <c>degrevlex</c>.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  The monomial ordering is passed as a named argument to the <c>PolynomialRing</c> constructor and is bound to the polynoial ring.
	  Note that <c>PolynomialRing</c> is immutable once constructed, so you will have to simply re-construct a polynomial ring if you wish to change the term order.
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    # Lex order on the rationals with three variables.
	    R.&lt;x,y,z> = PolynomialRing(QQ, order='lex')
	    print(R)
	    print(R.term_order())

	    f = -5*x^3 + 7*x^2*z^2 + 4*x*y^2*z + 4*z^2
	    # Sage automatically prints in term order.
	    print(f)
	    # Leading coefficient
	    print(f.lc())
	    # Leading monomial
	    print(f.lm())
	    # Leading term
	    print(f.lt())
	    # Multideg
	    print(f.lm().degrees()) # Method 1
	    print(f.lt().degrees()) # Method 2
	  </input>
	</sage>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    # Grlex order on the rationals with three variables.
	    R.&lt;x,y,z> = PolynomialRing(QQ, order='lex')
	    print(R)
	    print(R.term_order())

	    f = -5*x^3 + 7*x^2*z^2 + 4*x*y^2*z + 4*z^2
	    # Sage automatically prints in term order.
	    print(f)
	    # Leading coefficient
	    print(f.lc())
	    # Leading monomial
	    print(f.lm())
	    # Leading term
	    print(f.lt())
	    # Multideg
	    print(f.lm().degrees()) # Method 1
	    print(f.lt().degrees()) # Method 2
	  </input>
	</sage>

	<sage>
	  <input>
	    # Grevlex order on the rationals with three variables.
	    R.&lt;x,y,z> = PolynomialRing(QQ)
	    print(R)
	    print(R.term_order())
	    
	    f = -5*x^3 + 7*x^2*z^2 + 4*x*y^2*z + 4*z^2
	    # Sage automatically prints in term order.
	    print(f)
	    # Leading coefficient
	    print(f.lc())
	    # Leading monomial
	    print(f.lm())
	    # Leading term
	    print(f.lt())
	    # Multideg
	    print(f.lm().degrees()) # Method 1
	    print(f.lt().degrees()) # Method 2
	  </input>
	</sage>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="multivariate_division_algorithm">
    <title>Multivariate Division Algorithm</title>
    <p>
      Below is an implementation of the division algorithm.
      <alert>In order to use this function in other cells on the page, you need to click the <c>Evaluate (Sage)</c> button.</alert>
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
#Theorem 3
def npoly_div(f,F) :
    R = f.parent()

    s = len(F)
    qs = [R(0) for _ in F]
    r = R(0)
    p  = f

    while p != 0 :
        i = 0
        division_occurred = False
        print("i = %d:\r\n\r\tqs = [%s]\r\n\r\tr = %s" % (i,", ".join([str(q) for q in qs]),str(r)))
        while (i &lt; s) and not division_occurred:
            if p.lt() % F[i].lt() == 0:
                qs[i] = qs[i] + (p.lt()//F[i].lt())
                p = p - (p.lt()//F[i].lt())*F[i]
                division_occurred = True
                print("\r\tp = %s"%str(p))
            else:
                i += 1
        if not division_occurred:
            r = r + p.lt()
            p = p - p.lt()
    return qs,r
      </input>
    </sage>
    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Using lex order, divide the polynomial <m>f = xy^2 + 1</m> by <m>f_1 = xy + 1</m> and <m>f_2 = y + 1</m>.
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    #Example 1
	    R.&lt;x,y,z> = PolynomialRing(QQ,order="lex")
	    f = x*y^2 + 1
	    F = [x*y + 1, y + 1]
	    qs, r = npoly_div(f,F)
	    print("Result:\r\n\r\tqs = [%s]\r\n\r\tr = %s" % (", ".join([str(q) for q in qs]),str(r)))

	    #Check that (\sum_{i=1}^s q_i*f_i) + r is actually f.
	    print(f == sum(q*g for q, g in zip(qs, F)) + r)
	  </input>
	</sage>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-2_3_2">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Using lex order, divide the polynomial <m>f = x^2 y + xy^2 + y^2</m> by the polynomials <m>f_1 = xy - 1</m> and <m>f_2 = y^2 - 1</m>.
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    #Example 2
	    R.&lt;x,y,z> = PolynomialRing(QQ,order="lex")
	    f = x^2*y + x*y^2 + y^2
	    F = [x*y - 1, y^2 - 1]
	    qs, r = npoly_div(f,F)
	    print("Result:\r\n\r\tqs = [%s]\r\n\r\tr = %s" % (", ".join([str(q) for q in qs]),str(r)))

	    #Check that (\sum_{i=1}^s q_i*f_i) + r is actually f.
	    print(f == sum(q*g for q, g in zip(qs, F)) + r)
	  </input>
	</sage>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-2_3_4">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Using lex order, divide the polynomial <m>f = x^2 y + xy^2 + y^2</m> by the polynomials <m>f_1 = f_1 = y^2 - 1</m> and <m>f_2 = xy - 1</m>.
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    # Example 4
	    R.&lt;x,y,z> = PolynomialRing(QQ,order="lex")
	    f = x^2*y + x*y^2 + y^2
	    F = [y^2 - 1,x*y - 1]
	    qs, r = npoly_div(f,F)
	    print("Result:\r\n\r\tqs = [%s]\r\n\r\tr = %s" % (", ".join([str(q) for q in qs]),str(r)))

	    #Check that (\sum_{i=1}^s q_i*f_i) + r is actually f.
	    print(f == sum(q*g for q, g in zip(qs, F)) + r)
	  </input>
	</sage>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
	Note that <xref ref="example-2_3_2" text="type-local"/> and <xref ref="example-2_3_4" text="type-local"/> imply that the ordering of the <m>s</m>-tuple <m>F = (f_1, \ldots, f_s)</m> matters when dividing a polynomial <m>f</m> by <m>F</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
    
    <example xml:id="example-2_3_5">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Using lex order, divide the polynomial <m>f = x^2 y + xy^2 + y^2</m> by the polynomials <m>f_1 = y^2 - 1</m> and <m>f_2 = xy - 1</m>.
	  Then divide <m>f</m> by <m>f_1 = xy - 1</m> and <m>f_2 = y^2 - 1</m>
	</p>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    # Example 5
	    R.&lt;x,y,z> = PolynomialRing(QQ,order="lex")
	    f = x*y^2 - x
	    F = [x*y - 1, y^2 - 1]
	    qs, r = npoly_div(f,F)
	    print("Result:\r\n\r\tqs = [%s]\r\n\r\tr = %s" % (", ".join([str(q) for q in qs]),str(r)))

	    #Check that (\sum_{i=1}^s q_i*f_i) + r is actually f.
	    print(f == sum(q*g for q, g in zip(qs, F)) + r)
	  </input>
	</sage>
	<sage>
	  <input>
	    R.&lt;x,y,z> = PolynomialRing(QQ,order="lex")
	    f = x*y^2 - x
	    F = [y^2 - 1, x*y - 1]
	    qs, r = npoly_div(f,F)
	    print("Result:\r\n\r\tqs = [%s]\r\n\r\tr = %s" % (", ".join([str(q) for q in qs]),str(r)))

	    #Check that (\sum_{i=1}^s q_i*f_i) + r is actually f.
	    print(f == sum(q*g for q, g in zip(qs, F)) + r)
	  </input>
	</sage>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
	Note that <xref ref="example-2_3_5" text="type-local"/> implies the membership problem for multivariate polynomials rings is more subtle than for univariate polynomial rings!
	In <m>k[x]</m>, we saw that every ideal <m>I \subseteq k[x]</m> is generated by some <m>g \in k[x]</m>.
	Hence for all <m>f \in k[x]</m>, <m>f \in I \iff g \mid f</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
	The analogous statement for multivariate polynomials rings is the following.
	Let <m>I = \langle f_1, \ldots, f_s\rangle \subseteq k[x_1, \ldots, x_n]</m> be a finitely generated ideal.
	For all <m>f \in k[x_1, \ldots, x_s]</m>, <m>f \in I</m> if and only if the ordered <m>s</m>-tuple <m>F = (f_1, \ldots, f_s)</m> divides <m>f</m><mdash/><ie/>, the remainder on division of <m>f</m> by <m>F</m> is zero.
	It is clear that if the remainder on division of <m>f</m> by <m>F</m>, then <m>f \in I</m>.
	However, the converse is <alert>false</alert>.
      </p>
      <p>
	Changing the order of the generators does <em>not</em> change the ideal, so <m>I = \langle xy - 1, y^2 - 1\rangle = \langle y^2 - 1, xy - 1 \rangle</m>.
	The second computation above shows us that
	<md>f = x(y^2 - 1) + 0(xy - 1) \in I</md>,
	even though the reaminder on division by <m>F = (xy - 1, y^2 - 1)</m> is not zero.
	This suggests we require more sophisticated machinery to answer the multivariate ideal membership problem.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>
</section>
